      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">Portrait Video, Mobile Video</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Vertical video</strong> is video content shot or formatted in portrait orientation with a <strong>9:16 aspect ratio</strong>, designed to fill a mobile screen held upright. It is the native format for TikTok, Instagram Reels, YouTube Shorts, and Snapchat — platforms that collectively serve billions of video plays per day — and consistently earns higher watch time and engagement than landscape alternatives on those surfaces.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media / Video Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Portrait Video, Mobile Video</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">7 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">If your video strategy still defaults to 16:9 widescreen, you are optimising for a world that no longer exists. Over 80% of social video is watched on a phone held vertically. Every major short-form platform now treats 9:16 as its canonical format — and its algorithm as the reward mechanism for creators who use it.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is vertical video?</h2>
        <p>Vertical video refers to any video where the height is greater than the width. The dominant standard is the <strong>9:16 aspect ratio</strong> — the exact inverse of the 16:9 widescreen format used in television and cinema. At 1080p, that means 1080 pixels wide by 1920 pixels tall.</p>
        <p>The format became mainstream because smartphones are used in portrait mode roughly 94% of the time according to MOVR Mobile Overview Report data. When users watch a landscape video on a mobile feed, they see black bars above and below the content — a diminished experience that correlates with higher drop-off rates. Vertical video fills the whole screen, creating a more immersive and attention-holding experience.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>9:16 (full vertical):</strong> TikTok, Reels, Shorts, Snapchat Stories — fills the entire screen</li>
          <li><strong>4:5 (portrait, not full screen):</strong> Instagram feed posts — taller than square but not full vertical</li>
          <li><strong>1:1 (square):</strong> A compromise format — works across both mobile and desktop but optimises neither</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Platform signal</div>
          <p>TikTok, Instagram, and YouTube have all publicly stated that their algorithms <strong>prioritise native-format vertical content</strong> in their recommendation engines. A landscape video posted to Reels will reach fewer accounts than an equivalent vertical one, all else being equal.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why vertical video matters for marketers</h2>
        <p>Vertical video is not a creative preference — it is a distribution mechanism. Here is why it has become non-negotiable for social-first content teams:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Algorithm reach.</strong> TikTok's For You Page, Instagram's Explore, and YouTube Shorts' feed all favour content that matches the platform's native format. Vertical video signals to the algorithm that the creator understands the platform, which typically results in broader initial distribution.</li>
          <li><strong>Watch time.</strong> Full-screen video has fewer visual distractions (no bars, no surrounding interface) which keeps eyes on the content longer. Higher watch time signals quality to the algorithm, compounding the distribution advantage.</li>
          <li><strong>Video completion rate.</strong> Shorter vertical clips on Reels and TikTok consistently achieve completion rates of 30-60%, versus single-digit completion rates for long-form landscape content on the same platforms.</li>
          <li><strong>Ad performance.</strong> Meta's internal data shows vertical video ads in Stories and Reels placements deliver lower cost-per-view and higher click-through rates than landscape ads. The same budget buys more impressions in the correct format.</li>
          <li><strong>Content repurposing efficiency.</strong> A team that shoots vertical first can export to 1:1 for feed posts and crop to 16:9 for YouTube long-form with minimal quality loss. The reverse — shooting landscape and cropping to vertical — loses significant frame content.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How vertical video works on each platform</h2>
        <p>Each platform handles vertical video slightly differently. Understanding the nuances prevents costly reshoots and ensures your content is platform-optimised at the point of upload.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Platform</th><th>Format</th><th>Max Length</th><th>Safe Zone</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>TikTok</strong></td>
                <td>9:16</td>
                <td>10 min (Shorts: 60s)</td>
                <td>Keep text 250px from top &amp; bottom</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Instagram Reels</strong></td><td>9:16</td><td>90 seconds</td><td>Keep text 14% from edges</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>YouTube Shorts</strong></td><td>9:16</td><td>60 seconds</td><td>Avoid bottom 20% (subscribe button overlay)</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Snapchat</strong></td><td>9:16</td><td>60 seconds (ads)</td><td>Top 15% reserved for profile bar</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Facebook Stories</strong></td><td>9:16</td><td>20 seconds (ads)</td><td>Avoid top and bottom 14%</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>The "safe zone" concept is critical. Each platform overlays UI elements — username, caption, share buttons, CTAs — over the bottom and sometimes top of the video. Any text or key visual you place in those zones will be partially obscured. Always compose your shot with the safe zone in mind, not just the full frame.</p>

        <h2 id="shooting">How to shoot vertical video correctly</h2>
        <p>Shooting in 9:16 is not just about rotating your phone. It requires a different compositional mindset and, for professional productions, a different camera setup.</p>

        <h3>On mobile (smartphone)</h3>
        <p>The easiest path: shoot natively on your phone in portrait mode. Most modern flagship phones (iPhone 15 Pro, Samsung Galaxy S24 Ultra) can shoot 4K in portrait orientation. Use a vertical rig or gimbal designed for portrait shooting to eliminate shake. The DJI Osmo Mobile series and Insta360 stabilisers have dedicated vertical modes.</p>

        <h3>On a mirrorless or DSLR camera</h3>
        <p>Rotate the camera body 90 degrees and mount it on a vertical cage or L-bracket. Set the recording resolution to at least 1920x1080 (you will be outputting 1080x1920 after rotating in post). Alternatively, shoot in 4K landscape and use the extra resolution to reframe to 9:16 in post — you lose resolution but avoid physical rotation.</p>

        <h3>Composing for vertical</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Centre-frame subjects</strong> — vertical leaves less horizontal space, so subjects placed off-centre can fall out of the frame entirely on some displays.</li>
          <li><strong>Use the upper two-thirds</strong> for the main action — keep the bottom third clear for captions and UI overlays.</li>
          <li><strong>Avoid wide establishing shots</strong> — they read as tiny on vertical. Get closer, use tight framing, and rely on cutaways to convey space.</li>
          <li><strong>Text-on-screen</strong> is more effective in vertical than in landscape because the text fills the full width, making it larger and more readable at a glance.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="repurposing">Repurposing horizontal content into vertical</h2>
        <p>If you have an existing library of landscape (16:9) content, you can convert it to vertical — but the quality of the result depends heavily on the original framing and the conversion method you use.</p>

        <h3>AI auto-reframe tools</h3>
        <p>Adobe Premiere Pro's Auto Reframe, CapCut's Smart Crop, and DaVinci Resolve's Magic Mask can track the primary subject and dynamically pan-and-scan the crop as the subject moves. These tools work well when there is a single clear subject. They struggle with multi-person scenes, fast motion, and wide B-roll shots.</p>

        <h3>Manual reframe</h3>
        <p>For critical content (hero ads, brand campaigns), manual reframe in post is more reliable. An editor watches the original video and repositions the 9:16 crop frame by frame to follow the action. Time-intensive but produces the cleanest result.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">The pillarbox problem</div>
          <p>Never upload a landscape video to TikTok or Reels without first converting it. These platforms will display it with black pillarboxes (vertical black bars on both sides), which signals to viewers — and the algorithm — that this is recycled content. Reach drops dramatically for pillarboxed content.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for vertical video in 2026</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Shoot vertical first.</strong> Plan your production for 9:16 from the outset. Adapt to landscape for secondary distribution, not the reverse.</li>
          <li><strong>Hook in 1-2 seconds.</strong> Feeds are designed for swiping. The first second must give viewers a reason to stop. Start mid-action, ask a provocative question, or show the payoff before the explanation.</li>
          <li><strong>Add captions.</strong> 85% of social video is watched without sound in public. Open captions (burned in, not just uploaded as a separate file) ensure your message lands regardless of sound settings.</li>
          <li><strong>Respect safe zones.</strong> Check each platform's safe zone template and keep all critical text and graphics within the clear area. Overlapping UI elements ruin otherwise good content.</li>
          <li><strong>Use music and trending audio.</strong> On TikTok and Reels, using a trending sound boosts distribution. The algorithm correlates audio trends with timely content discovery.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep essential info high on screen.</strong> The bottom third is consistently obscured by the caption overlay and interactive stickers. Place your brand logo and key messages in the upper 60% of the frame.</li>
          <li><strong>Batch produce.</strong> Vertical video works best at volume — consistency of posting matters as much as individual video quality. Set up batch production sessions where you film 5-10 clips in one go, reducing per-video time cost significantly.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common vertical video mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Leaving black bars.</strong> Any platform will penalise cropped landscape content with visible bars — remove them or do not post in that format.</li>
          <li><strong>Slow intros.</strong> Branded title cards, long logos, and slow zooms in the first five seconds destroy retention. Get to the point immediately.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring safe zones.</strong> Text and logos covered by the platform UI look unprofessional and communicate the wrong information.</li>
          <li><strong>Identical content across platforms.</strong> TikTok, Reels, and Shorts each have different audiences, audio cultures, and caption styles. A video optimised for one rarely lands equally well on all three without adaptation.</li>
          <li><strong>No sound strategy.</strong> Posting vertical video without either captions or audio optimisation means you lose the segment of viewers watching on mute and the segment that needs trending audio to discover you.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="vs-horizontal">Vertical video vs horizontal video — when to use each</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use vertical (9:16) for</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>TikTok, Reels, Shorts, Snapchat</li>
              <li>Mobile-first paid social ads</li>
              <li>Stories placements on all platforms</li>
              <li>Quick tutorials, behind-the-scenes</li>
              <li>Trending audio or challenge content</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use horizontal (16:9) for</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>YouTube long-form videos</li>
              <li>LinkedIn video posts (desktop-heavy audience)</li>
              <li>Website hero videos and embedded players</li>
              <li>Webinars and screen-share recordings</li>
              <li>TV or CTV ad placements</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What aspect ratio is vertical video?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Vertical video uses a 9:16 aspect ratio — 1080 pixels wide by 1920 pixels tall at full HD resolution. This fills the entire screen of a phone held upright, which is how most people hold their phones while browsing social media.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Does vertical video perform better than landscape video on social media?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Meta, TikTok, and YouTube all report that vertical video generates higher completion rates and better engagement than landscape when served on mobile feeds. Platforms algorithmically reward full-screen native formats, which means vertical content is shown to more people for less ad spend.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can I repurpose a landscape video into vertical format?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>You can, but cropping a wide video to 9:16 often cuts off subjects and text. The better approach is to shoot with vertical in mind from the start, or use auto-reframe AI tools (available in Adobe Premiere, CapCut, and DaVinci Resolve) that intelligently track the subject during the crop.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Which platforms require vertical video?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>TikTok, Instagram Reels, YouTube Shorts, and Snapchat are all designed around vertical video as the primary format. Facebook and LinkedIn will accept vertical but are less optimised for it. For maximum reach, produce in 9:16 first and adapt to other ratios as needed.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How long should a vertical video be?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Optimal length varies by platform: TikTok and Reels perform best at 15-60 seconds for discovery content, though longer videos (up to 3 minutes) work for educational content. YouTube Shorts cap at 60 seconds. The single most important rule is to hook viewers in the first 1-2 seconds to prevent a swipe away.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

